# Comments

Write comments only when they add information the code cannot convey on its own.
Prefer clear names and small functions over explanatory comments.

## Do comment

- **Why**, not what: non-obvious intent, trade-offs, constraints, workarounds.
- Gotchas a reader would otherwise hit (e.g. ordering requirements, env quirks).
- Links to a spec/issue when the reasoning lives elsewhere.

## Don't comment

- Restating the code or narrating steps (`// increment counter`, `// import x`).
- Section banners, redundant JSDoc that repeats the signature, commented-out code.
- Explaining the change you just made (that belongs in the commit message).

```ts
// ❌ BAD — narrates the obvious
// loop over points and project them
points.map((p) => project(p));

// ✅ GOOD — explains a non-obvious constraint
// d3 mutates the scale's domain in place, so clone before reuse.
const safeScale = scale.copy();
```

Descriptive test names usually replace per-assertion comments. If a comment
risks going stale, delete it or encode the fact in code instead.
